Market Study - Food Industry Exports

Openclassrooms, Data Analyst Course
Project 5 - Michael Orange

A company in the food industry specialized in Chicken Meat is looking at expanding worldwide. All countries are considered.

Production is located in France.
The mission is to provide the company with data ensuring it will collaborate with the most promising export market countries.

Grouping countries in 'clusters' based on their similarity is required.
Default variables are:

  • population growth,
  • calory supply per capita
  • protein supply per capita,
  • prevalence of animal proteins in the mix.

Additional relevant variable might be included (ex. GDP per capita)

Section 1 - Import Datasets

Section 2 - Preparation

  • Data overview
  • Testing the normality of the distributions
  • Transform data - power transform to normal distributions
  • Transform data - mean centering and variance standardization

Section 3 - PCA - Principal Component Analysis

  • Number of components
  • Hierarchical Clustering after PCA
  • Synthetic variables
  • Correlation Circles
  • Individuals factor map
  • Centroids

Section 4 - Analysis of the clusters

  • Exportation to high income developped countries
    • Exportation to EU countries
    • Exportation to non-EU developped countries
  • Final selection: 5 EU countries and 2 non EU countries

Section 5 - Statistical tests to compare clusters

  • Shapiro test
  • Test for equality of Variances
  • Two-Sample t-test for Equal Means

Preparation

Data overview

  • pop_growth = growth of the population (2103-2017)
  • gdp_per_capita_usd = GDP per capita in USD (2017)
  • political_stability_index = Index of the Political Stability and Absence of Violence (2017)
  • food_supply_kcalcapitaday = Food supply in kcal/capita/day (2017)
  • protein_supply_gcapitaday = Protein supply in g /capita/day (2017)
  • protein_animal_over_protein = Food pourcentage of proteins from Animals over the total proteins (2017)
  • growth_protein_animal_gcapitaday = growth of the protein animal per capita (2013-2017)
  • protein_poultry_gcapitaday = protein supply from Poultry in g/capita/day (2017)
  • prod_poultry_over_domsupply = Production Poultry over Domestic Supply Poultry (2017)
  • net_import_poultry_over_domsupply = (Imports - Exports) over Domestic Supply Poultry (2017)
  • growth_net_import_poultry = growth of the net imports of Poultry (2013-2017)
  • growth_domsupply_poultry = growth of the domestic supply of Poultry (2013-2017)

Significant outliers:

  • Population growth higher than 20% : ['Oman']
  • GDP per capita higher than 65 000 : ['Luxembourg']
  • Import of Poultry 300+ % higher than internal consumption : ['China, Hong Kong SAR']
  • Net Import (Import - Export) of Poultry at least 300% lower than domestic supply : ['Netherlands', 'Belgium']
  • 600+ % growth of Poultry Imports : ['Cambodia', 'Turkmenistan']
  • 200+ % gowth of Poulry Domestic Supply : ['Malawi', 'Mozambique']

Testing the normality of the distributions

The Shapiro-Wilk test evaluates variable's values and quantifies how likely it is that the data are from a Gaussian distribution.

  • H0: Gaussian distribution
  • H1: Not a Gaussian distribution
In [14]:
X_not_gaussian =[]
significance_level = 0.01
for X in data_pca.columns: 
    stat, pvalue = stats.shapiro(data_pca[X])
    if pvalue < significance_level:
        print('{}: --------Normal distribution not confirmed, H0 rejected with pvalue= {}'.format(X, pvalue))
        X_not_gaussian.append(X)

Transform data - power transform to normal distributions

In order to improve the results of the below PCA, a transformation is done using 'box_cox' (for strictly positive variables) and 'yeo-johnson' (for variables with negative values) methods.

In [16]:
X_totransform = X_not_gaussian
In [17]:
#Apply a power transform featurewise to make data more Gaussian-like. 
for i in range(len(X_totransform)):
    if (data_pca[X_totransform[i]]>0).all() == True:
        pt = preprocessing.PowerTransformer(method='box-cox', copy=False)
    else:
        pt = preprocessing.PowerTransformer(method='yeo-johnson', copy=False)
    
    data = data_pca[X_totransform[i]].values.reshape(-1,1)
    pt.fit(data)
    preprocessing.PowerTransformer()
    pt.transform(data)
    data_pca[X_totransform[i]] = data

Analysis of the clusters

The Poultry market is a strong competitive market. The international Poultry market, whose growth is being powered by emerging countries, is focusing on cost rather than quality.
Cost is the strategic variable for success in most of the geographies.

In poultry production, French farms are more numerous and also smaller than the ones from the main producers (Brazil, USA, Thailand, China, Poland, etc.). French poultry farms have a smaller capacity because of the importance of quality and origin labels (Red Label, organic, Appellation dOrigine Contrle).
With farm sizes which dont allow for large economies of scale, and with labour costs above some of its competitors, the French Poultry sector is facing challenges on exports.

With a gourmet image and high quality products, it is recommended for a French Poultry producer to explore export markets with a clientele ready to pay for premium products. Countries with a higher level of development are preferred.
For French poultry producers, exportation to EU countries is facilitated in terms of regulations, standards and import tariffs.

Exportation to high-income developed countries

Cluster 5 is our cluster of choice witht the best country attributes regarding the level of development, net importations and growth of the local demand for Poultry products.
['Albania', 'Austria', 'Barbados', 'Bulgaria', 'Canada', 'Cyprus', 'Denmark', 'Estonia', 'Finland', 'France', 'Germany', 'Greece', 'China, Hong Kong SAR', 'Hungary', 'Croatia', 'Iceland', 'Ireland', 'Italy', 'Japan', 'Republic of Korea', 'Latvia', 'Lithuania', 'China, Macao SAR', 'Malta', 'Mauritius', 'New Zealand', 'Norway', 'Czechia', 'Portugal', 'Romania', 'Slovenia', 'Slovakia', 'Spain', 'Sweden', 'Switzerland', 'China, Taiwan Province of', 'United Arab Emirates', 'United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland', 'Luxembourg', 'Montenegro']

The countries in Cluster 5 bordering on France are: Switzerland, Luxembourg, Spain, Germany and United Kingdom.

Selected:

  • Switzerland: There is a decrease of the Poultry imports between 2013-2017. However due to the very close distance from France, their high GDP per capita, and the significant size of their Poultry net importations, Switzerland remains in the selection.
  • Luxembourg: The size of the market is quite limited. However due to the very close distance from France, their belonging to EU, their very high GDP per capita and their strong dependance to Poultry importations (0 local production), Luxembourg remains in the selection.
  • Germany: no arbitrage required for Germany. It is a natural choice (matching all criterias) in our selection. See below.

Not in the selection:

  • United Kingdom: With a decrease of their importations (due to an increase of their production) combined to an unstability caused by the Brexit, the United Kingdom is not selected.
  • Spain: Spain has a significant poultry production exceeding the needs of their domestic market and exporting to other countries.

Non-EU selection in Cluster 5
['United Arab Emirates', 'Switzerland']

Switzerland is not part of the EU but needs to remain a high priority objective in terms of exports due to the close distance (by road) with France and the bilateral trade agreements between France and Switzerland. Despite the decline of importations, Switzerland remains an attractive export opportunity with a significant market size due to an insufficient production.

United Arab Emirates presents an interesting business opportunity with a significant volume of importations, a significant growth of both importations and domestic supply and a high GDP per capita. In addition, the UAE are highly dependant on importations due to a very low production inferior to 15% (with limited possibilities for a change due to hot weather)..

Not Selected
Taiwan Distant from France, Taiwan is an interesting option due to a high level of development, a significant volume of Poultry importations combined with a strong growth of the importations (38%). However Taiwan has complex relationship with China and a strong political ties with the USA. That dependence is observed on the quantity of chicken imported from the North-America (USA and Canada) accounting for 99.8% of their importations

Note: Japan is the first worldwide market in terms of importations. It has been not included from the selection mainly due to a decline of their internal domestic supply (higher than their population decline) combined with a very strong increase of their Poultry production - +51% - during the same period (2013-2017). While their demand is decreasing, their production capacity is now exceeding 90%. Their production could meet in the future their internal demand.

Final selection: 5 EU countries and 2 non EU countries

EU countries selected: ['Austria', 'Germany', 'Czechia', 'Sweden', 'Luxembourg']

Key figures:

  • total Population : 112,616,150 inhabitants

  • total Poultry importations : 1,163,000 tons
  • a high GDP per capita of 41,467 USD (average).
  • a high level of proteins per capita of 102 g per capita a day.

Statistical tests to compare clusters

Shapiro test

In [44]:
X = 'protein_supply_gcapitaday'

stat, pvalue = stats.shapiro(data_country[X])
print('{}: -----Gaussian-like distribution, H0 not rejected at 1% significance level with pvalue= {}'.format(X, pvalue))

protein_supply_gcapitaday: -----Gaussian-like distribution, H0 not rejected at 1% significance level with pvalue= 0.010924579575657845

With a significance level of 1%, we cannot reject the null hypothesis for 'protein_supply_gcapitaday'.
Therefore we cannot reject the hypothesis that values of 'protein_supply_gcapitaday' in our dataset is following a normal distribution.

Test for Equality of Variances

In [47]:
stat, pvalue = stats.bartlett(cluster_protein[0], cluster_protein[1])
if pvalue < 0.05: 
    print('{} vs {} ----------------------------------------------------------- statistic: {}, pvalue: {}'.format(G_names[0], G_names[1], stat, pvalue))
else:
    print('{} vs {} - null hypothesis not rejected (>5%) -  statistic: {}, pvalue: {}'.format(G_names[0], G_names[1], stat, pvalue))

cluster 5 vs cluster 10 - null hypothesis not rejected (>5%) -  statistic: 1.9544499186749094, pvalue: 0.1621081355480104

Using a significance level of 5%, we cannot reject the null hypothesis for cluster 5 compared to cluster 10.
Cluter 5 and Cluster 10 have an equivalent variance at this level of significance.

Two-Sample t-Test for Equal Means

In [48]:
stat, pvalue = stats.ttest_ind(cluster_protein[0], cluster_protein[1], equal_var=True)
if pvalue < 0.05: 
    print('{} vs {} ----------------------------------------------------------- statistic: {}, pvalue: {}'.format(G_names[0], G_names[1], stat, pvalue))
else:
    print('{} vs {} - null hypothesis not rejected (>5%) -  statistic: {}, pvalue: {}'.format(G_names[0], G_names[1], stat, pvalue))

cluster 5 vs cluster 10 ----------------------------------------------------------- statistic: 10.942768711192889, pvalue: 1.5789988578749275e-15

Using a significance level of 5%, we can reject the null hypothesis. Countries in Cluster 5 and 10 do not have the same level of proteins per capita.
